<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.digikitten.com/playhousev2/files/Weeble/Sleepin.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p>Searching for Mommy for 19 (Oops, back to 18)(Hey, back to 19) seasons now</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=statholturris>Stathol Turris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 313<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/15/03 11:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3868.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Spelling and age. (or should be it speling?)</span><hr size=1> Well, for starters, I have a lot of respect for someone who can speak more than one language with anything that comes even remotely close to fluency. I took 6 years of Spanish in grade school, but I wouldn't really say that I can speak Spanish. I understand how difficult languages can be for a lot of people, myself included.<br>
<br>
That said, when people criticize spelling and grammar in posts, it's because they assume you're a native speaker. Is that arrogance? I don't think it is. I think it's just a matter of statistics. There's a fair number of people playing Everquest that don't speak English as their first language, but nonetheless, I'd wager that at <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>least</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 95% of the people I've met do. It's really not such an unreasonable assumption that the person you're speaking to is a native English-speaker. But that's just a small part of it.<br>
<br>
It's easy to say that &quot;Americans think the world revolves around them&quot;, but I think that comes from not really understanding the geographical differences between Europe and the U.S. Simply put, the U.S. is geographically *huge*. A lot of it is empty space, sure, but the simple fact remains that a person in the center of the U.S. can literally travel for thousands of miles in any direction and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>still</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be in a (predominantly) English-speaking country. Even living in one of the southern-most states of the U.S., I still have to go about 600 miles before I reach the Mexican border. Europe is a very different story. Every three or four hundred miles you're in a different country where a different language is spoken. It's not so odd, in that context, to think that someone speaking Czech, for example, might not be Czechoslovakian. In the U.S., the exceedingly large probability is that anyone who speaks English speaks it as their first language, or at least as a concurrent first language with Spanish.<br>
<br>
That tends to color your perception of things like the internet, too. It's also why a lot of Americans (allthought the number is dropping) only speak one language. It's not arrogance, it's just utility. There's really not any practical reason to learn any language other than English if you live in the U.S., and Americans are very practical. You can live your entire life in the U.S. speaking only English, and never be inconvenienced by it. In that context, other languages kind of become like learning how to paint or play the violin. A good thing to do, and it's nice thing to know, but it's hardly necessary. And with modern life being as busy as it is, the unecessary things are usually the first to go. It's really nothing personal. The evolution of English as a sort of &quot;common language&quot; on the Internet hasn't helped the situation.<br>
<br>
Which brings up the issue of the Internet and the usage of English as a common language. The U.S. has taken a lot of flak for this, but honestly it's just an economic thing. The vast majority of Americans don't expect people outside of the U.S. to speak English. Honestly. But it's a numbers game. So many of the big international businesses are based in the U.S. that it puts you at a disadvantage if you can't communicate with them. On top of that, the native-English-speaking market is huge - bigger than any other language market except for maybe Cantonese or Mandarin, but China isn't exactly a free-market kind of place. Not being able to market your product in English cuts out a huge opportunity for profit: 280 million people in the U.S. + 60 million in the U.K + 20 million in Australia + 30 million in Canada = 390 million people. That's just too tempting of a market to ignore. Conversely, what language would a U.S. company want to be able to deal in? German? French? In order to pick up a market the size of the one they already have, they'd have to learn a dozen languages. The incentive just isn't big enough to affect large-scale social change. And frankly, a lot of countries have taken up English as a secondary language because it's useful when everyone around you speaks a different language. It's kind of nice to have a common language that everyone speaks so that you only need to learn one additional language instead of 5. English makes a pretty logical choice for the reasons I mentioned above, and because it's not a very critical language as a whole, making it a fairly easy language to learn for most people who already speak something in the Indo-European language family. Like I said, English can be butchered pretty badly but still be undrestood. And as a general rule of the thumb, English speakers don't get too pissy if you do. Which brings us back to the issue at hand...<br>
<br>
So the end result is that people on these boards just kind of assume that if you speak English, it's your first language, unless you inform them otherwise. Right, wrong, or indifferent, they do. And if you're trying to argue with someone, a very cheap and easy way to call their intelligence into question is to critique their spelling and grammar. It's not especially relevant, and as you've pointed out, it's not a fair shot against non-native speakers, but it's easy to do, so people do it. It's not even about the language itself, it's about making look like the person who made the post can't even speak their own language correctly. It would be the same story for any language. And while it does go overboard, there are times when someone's post is so poorly written that there's just no excuse for it. Not using punction, for example. Nobody expects anyone to get commas in all the right places, but just a simple period at the end of sentences is good. How many times have you seen a post like this its not very easy to understand is it i dont see why people do it.... I mean, really. I *know* that nearly every other language in the world makes use of basic punctuation to separate ideas. There probably are some exceptions, but they're very few and far between.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that's about it for my long diatribe. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=birgette>Birgette</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/15/03 11:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3868.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Spelling and age. (or should be it speling?)</span><hr size=1> ~kindly thanks Stathol for her/his diatribe, and offers her/him a lemming~  There, there...  it will all be over soon. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/b_angel517/images/BirgSig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=viala>Viala</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/15/03 12:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3868.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Spelling and age. (or should be it speling?)</span><hr size=1> Criticising people for their grammar or spelling is just rude and I wouldn't do it. Cultural and linguistic differences aside. Some people might think I should use a 'z' in the first word of this paragraph, for instance - now there's a hornet's nest. I just prefer the old British spellings.<br>
